<span class="meta-label uppercase">Reading List</span>
</div>
<div class="column entry-content">
<article class="reading-list-item">
<div class='sections' style='color: #2c5b53;'>Economy &amp; Labor</div>
<a href="https://truthout.org/articles/a-big-oil-bailout-would-be-the-opposite-of-the-green-new-deal-we-need/">A Big Oil Bailout Would Be the Opposite of the Green New Deal We Need</a>
</article>
<article class="reading-list-item">
<div class='sections' style='color: #2c5b53;'>Economy &amp; Labor</div>
<a href="https://truthout.org/articles/covid-19-was-a-trigger-but-capitalism-caused-the-economic-crash/">COVID-19 Was a Trigger, But Capitalism Caused the Economic Crash</a>
</article>
<article class="reading-list-item">
<div class='sections' style='color: #0ba864;'>Environment &amp; Health</div>
<a href="https://truthout.org/articles/covid-19-may-increase-heat-extremes-this-summer/">COVID-19 May Increase Heat Extremes This Summer</a>
</article>
<article class="reading-list-item">
<div class='sections' style='color: #1958aa;'>Politics &amp; Elections</div>
<a href="https://truthout.org/articles/trumps-lies-are-killing-his-supporters-as-covid-starts-to-sweep-rural-america/">Trump&#8217;s Lies Are Killing His Supporters as COVID Starts to Sweep Rural America</a>
</article>
<article class="reading-list-item">
<div class='sections' style='color: #cc822e;'>Prisons &amp; Policing</div>
<a href="https://truthout.org/articles/where-im-incarcerated-people-with-covid-19-are-warehoused-in-a-gym/">Where I’m Incarcerated, People With COVID-19 Are Warehoused in a Gym</a>
</article>
<article class="reading-list-item">
<div class='sections' style='color: #0ba864;'>Environment &amp; Health</div>
<a href="https://truthout.org/articles/a-covid-19-vaccine-will-not-be-enough-we-need-a-plan-to-distribute-it/">A COVID-19 Vaccine Will Not Be Enough &#8212; We Need a Plan to Distribute It</a>
</article>
</div>
</aside>
</div>
<div class="entry-content primary-content-column columns small-12 medium-8">
<p>In the debate about what strategy to adopt to combat climate change, the Green New Deal has quickly become the new buzzword on the left. Is it an insufficient social-democratic response to the present crisis, or is it, in fact, the only realistic project we have to save the planet? Robert Pollin, distinguished professor of economics and co-director of the Political Economy Research Institute at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst, is a leading proponent of a green future and he shared his vision of the Green New Deal in the interview below, which appeared originally in Swedish in the left paper <a href="https://flamman.se/a/det-enda-realistiska-projektet"><em>Flamman</em></a>.</p>
<p><strong>Jonas Elvander: You are one of the most well-known scientific spokespersons for a so-called &ldquo;Green New Deal.&rdquo; Can you explain what that means?</strong></p>
<p><strong>Robert Pollin: </strong>In my view, the core features of the Green New Deal are quite simple. They consist of a worldwide program to invest between 2-3 percent of global GDP every year to dramatically raise energy efficiency standards and equally dramatically expand lean renewable energy supplies.</p><div class="truth-post-content-high  inline-callout-container" id="truth-255792"><aside class=" callout inline-callout callout--subscribe callout--dark" id="truth-255397">
<h2>The stories you care about, right at your fingertips</h2>
<p>Get <em>Truthout&rsquo;</em>s daily edition delivered to your inbox.</p>
